00:00:53.370 --> 00:00:55.950
CHARLIE BRINSON: Yeah, my name
is Charlie Brinson, and I'm

00:00:55.950 --> 00:00:57.470
the initiator of this project.

00:00:57.470 --> 00:01:01.510
The project's called Titanoboa,
and it's a massive

00:01:01.510 --> 00:01:04.209
recreation of this ancient snake
that used to exist 60

00:01:04.209 --> 00:01:04.830
million years ago.

00:01:04.830 --> 00:01:07.170
FITZ: And just how big
is this snake?

00:01:07.170 --> 00:01:08.510
CHARLIE BRINSON: Right
now, this one is

00:01:08.510 --> 00:01:09.780
about 40 feet long.

00:01:09.780 --> 00:01:13.050
But it's still in the process of
growing, so we're going to

00:01:13.050 --> 00:01:17.160
lengthen it to 50 feet to
represent the original kind of

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:18.750
beast that was roaming
the Earth.

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:22.260
BEN: Now, when you say this
project, who is this group

00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:23.170
that you're in charge of here?

00:01:23.170 --> 00:01:25.900
CHARLIE BRINSON: So I'm the
initiator of the project, and

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:29.760
we have a team of about
15 or 20 people.

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:32.600
We're all working under the
support of a foundation called

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:35.060
eatART, which is Energy
Awareness Through ART.

00:01:35.060 --> 00:01:38.040
And we build huge kinetic
sculptures that have

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:39.350
energy-related themes to them.

00:01:39.350 --> 00:01:41.100
BEN: What is the energy-related

00:01:41.100 --> 00:01:42.380
theme for this sculpture?

00:01:42.380 --> 00:01:45.160
CHARLIE BRINSON: Well, we figure
since the story goes

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:48.190
that Titanoboa went extinct 60
million years ago because the

00:01:48.190 --> 00:01:50.270
climate cooled down, right?

00:01:50.270 --> 00:01:53.730
So now the climate's warming
back up, so we're resurrecting

00:01:53.730 --> 00:01:57.580
this beast to get discussions
going about climate change and

00:01:57.580 --> 00:02:00.632
showcase electric vehicle
technology.

00:02:00.632 --> 00:02:02.300
FITZ: What kind of
locomotion--

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:04.570
does this actually move
like a snake?

00:02:04.570 --> 00:02:05.220
CHARLIE BRINSON: Yeah.

00:02:05.220 --> 00:02:08.210
So you can see down the spine
there's all these hydraulic

00:02:08.210 --> 00:02:11.310
cylinders, which are muscles
of the snake.

00:02:11.310 --> 00:02:14.150
And they contract in such a
way that it enables it to

00:02:14.150 --> 00:02:15.250
propel itself.

00:02:15.250 --> 00:02:17.970
So it's all controlled by a
series of microcontroller

00:02:17.970 --> 00:02:20.910
brains all down the spine
and controlled

00:02:20.910 --> 00:02:22.635
wirelessly from the driver.

00:02:22.635 --> 00:02:24.680
FITZ: And how fast does it go?

00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:26.475
Should we be concerned?

00:02:26.475 --> 00:02:29.850
CHARLIE BRINSON: Yeah, sometimes
it gets a little bit

00:02:29.850 --> 00:02:32.030
of a temper going, and it
can lash out its tail.

00:02:32.030 --> 00:02:36.100
But you could probably outrun it
pretty easily, at least at

00:02:36.100 --> 00:02:36.720
this stage.

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:39.000
We're planning on modifying it
and upgrading it so that it

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:40.550
can really cruise.

00:02:40.550 --> 00:02:42.670
BEN: Are any of the attendees
here going to get a chance to

00:02:42.670 --> 00:02:44.910
drive this thing, or
is it experts only?

00:02:44.910 --> 00:02:47.800
CHARLIE BRINSON: There's a
pretty big learning curve.

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:51.620
Because it can flick its tail
out and stuff, you've got to

00:02:51.620 --> 00:02:53.460
go through a rigorous training
program before you can

00:02:53.460 --> 00:02:54.910
actually get behind the--

00:02:54.910 --> 00:02:55.500
BEN: Excellent.

00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:57.210
