00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:04.940
FITZ: So what's your name?

00:04:04.940 --> 00:04:06.310
CHRISTIAN RISTOW: Christian
Ristow.

00:04:06.310 --> 00:04:08.330
FITZ: And Christian, tell us a
little bit about what we're

00:04:08.330 --> 00:04:10.942
standing in front of, and
are we in danger?

00:04:10.942 --> 00:04:13.420
CHRISTIAN RISTOW: You are
not actually in danger.

00:04:13.420 --> 00:04:16.029
It might be fun to think you
are, but I have other pieces

00:04:16.029 --> 00:04:19.390
that would endanger you
more than this one is.

00:04:19.390 --> 00:04:21.649
This piece is called
Face Forward.

00:04:21.649 --> 00:04:25.260
And it's a 12-foot tall
animatronic human face made

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:28.390
from aluminum and
stainless steel.

00:04:28.390 --> 00:04:30.630
It's radio-controlled.

00:04:30.630 --> 00:04:33.950
There are 12 points of control
on the face that correspond to

00:04:33.950 --> 00:04:37.640
different elements of human
facial expression.

00:04:37.640 --> 00:04:41.140
And each of those control points
is controlled from a

00:04:41.140 --> 00:04:42.770
control station.

00:04:42.770 --> 00:04:46.240
And they're spaced and arranged
in such a way that

00:04:46.240 --> 00:04:48.960
one person can really only
operate one at a time.

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:50.785
So the idea is that it takes
12 people to bring

00:04:50.785 --> 00:04:51.970
the piece to life.

00:04:51.970 --> 00:04:55.520
BEN: Can you tell us what
inspired you to build this?

00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:59.730
CHRISTIAN RISTOW: Basically,
I started getting, at some

00:04:59.730 --> 00:05:03.920
point, very interested in
the idea of human facial

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:09.880
expression and the musculature
associated with it because

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:10.550
it's fascinating.

00:05:10.550 --> 00:05:13.800
We have this amazingly
sensitive, expressive

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:16.660
musculature in our face, which
is devoted to one thing and

00:05:16.660 --> 00:05:17.370
one thing only, and that's

00:05:17.370 --> 00:05:20.210
communication with other people.

00:05:20.210 --> 00:05:23.380
And it functions in ways that
are more subtle and intricate

00:05:23.380 --> 00:05:24.550
than we realize.

00:05:24.550 --> 00:05:27.390
And we can even occasionally
express things to other people

00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:28.570
that we don't really mean to.

00:05:28.570 --> 00:05:32.320
And so it's just fascinating,
and I really wanted to build a

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:35.180
piece that captured
that somehow.

00:05:35.180 --> 00:05:38.130
And then, almost as an
afterthought, I came up with

00:05:38.130 --> 00:05:42.080
this idea of spreading out the
controls and making it

00:05:42.080 --> 00:05:44.830
something that would require
12 people to

00:05:44.830 --> 00:05:45.950
really bring to life.

00:05:45.950 --> 00:05:50.590
And there's an element of an
experiment in cooperation

00:05:50.590 --> 00:05:51.840
built into the piece.

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:58.750
There's a degree to which
I have always hoped that

00:05:58.750 --> 00:06:03.580
spontaneous cooperation would
emerge among groups of people.

00:06:03.580 --> 00:06:07.390
And certain people would perhaps
take on the role of

00:06:07.390 --> 00:06:11.560
leader, like OK, everybody,
let's do anger!

00:06:11.560 --> 00:06:16.580
And so I have really wanted to
watch the groups of people

00:06:16.580 --> 00:06:18.700
controlling the face and wait
and see if something like that

00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:19.110
would happen.

00:06:19.110 --> 00:06:20.310
It has happened.

00:06:20.310 --> 00:06:21.920
It has happened much less
frequently than

00:06:21.920 --> 00:06:22.845
I thought it might.

00:06:22.845 --> 00:06:24.440
BEN: It's fantastic.

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:26.730
The whole idea of emergent
collaboration is something

00:06:26.730 --> 00:06:30.406
that's very near and dear
to our heart, in fact.

00:06:30.406 --> 00:06:31.885
It's fascinating stuff.

