00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:23.286
PROF.

00:07:23.286 --> 00:07:24.980
RAFFAELLO D'ANDREA: It's
Raffaello D'Andrea.

00:07:24.980 --> 00:07:26.710
FITZ: And where are
you from, and what

00:07:26.710 --> 00:07:27.830
exactly is going on here?

00:07:27.830 --> 00:07:27.963
PROF.

00:07:27.963 --> 00:07:30.000
RAFFAELLO D'ANDREA: I'm a
professor at the Swiss Federal

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:31.540
Institute of Technology.

00:07:31.540 --> 00:07:33.810
And what you're seeing here
is a demonstration of

00:07:33.810 --> 00:07:35.630
multi-vehicle control.

00:07:35.630 --> 00:07:39.770
These flying vehicles are
collaborating to throw a ball

00:07:39.770 --> 00:07:41.660
up in the air and then
collaborating to

00:07:41.660 --> 00:07:42.350
move and catch it.

00:07:42.350 --> 00:07:44.105
FITZ: They're really good.

00:07:44.105 --> 00:07:44.220
PROF.

00:07:44.220 --> 00:07:45.110
RAFFAELLO D'ANDREA: Yeah,
they're quite good at it.

00:07:45.110 --> 00:07:47.260
There's no way that you could
have human beings control

00:07:47.260 --> 00:07:48.770
these vehicles to do this.

00:07:48.770 --> 00:07:49.880
They're fully autonomous.

00:07:49.880 --> 00:07:53.970
They're not remote-controlled
by human beings.

00:07:53.970 --> 00:07:56.190
And the precision required
to do this is not

00:07:56.190 --> 00:07:57.990
achievable with people.

00:07:57.990 --> 00:08:00.470
It has to be done autonomously
with sophisticated algorithms.

00:08:00.470 --> 00:08:04.020
BEN: Are they actually tracking
the ball as it falls

00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:04.960
back down to the ground?

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:05.060
PROF.

00:08:05.060 --> 00:08:05.560
RAFFAELLO D'ANDREA: They are.

00:08:05.560 --> 00:08:08.180
The vehicles themselves
are not.

00:08:08.180 --> 00:08:10.760
Because we're indoors here, we
have an indoor GPS system,

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:14.560
which is the equivalent
of GPS outside.

00:08:14.560 --> 00:08:18.180
And that is what we're using
to track the vehicles.

00:08:18.180 --> 00:08:20.410
The ball is being tracked as
it flies, and then the

00:08:20.410 --> 00:08:22.500
vehicles figure out exactly
where they need to be to

00:08:22.500 --> 00:08:23.296
intercept it.

00:08:23.296 --> 00:08:25.880
BEN: That is amazing,
absolutely amazing.

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:27.850
FITZ: And so how big
is your team?

00:08:27.850 --> 00:08:27.946
PROF.

00:08:27.946 --> 00:08:30.830
RAFFAELLO D'ANDREA: So we have
a rather large team here.

00:08:30.830 --> 00:08:32.159
We have about six people here.

00:08:32.159 --> 00:08:35.179
We have another 10
folks back home.

00:08:35.179 --> 00:08:36.970
We do research on autonomous
systems,

00:08:36.970 --> 00:08:38.740
not just flying vehicles.

00:08:38.740 --> 00:08:41.225
So it's a team of
about 15 people.

