RAFFAELLO D'ANDREA: Right.

00:08:47.250 --> 00:08:50.550
So these things are actually
quite robust.

00:08:50.550 --> 00:08:53.000
A lot of times, we fly them,
they bounce on the ground, and

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:53.630
they get back up.

00:08:53.630 --> 00:08:57.285
But we've probably gone through
10, 20 vehicles.

00:08:57.285 --> 00:09:00.660
BEN: Our people who are watching
this at home, they

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:01.860
are developers.

00:09:01.860 --> 00:09:04.300
Are they able to play with
autonomous systems like this?

00:09:04.300 --> 00:09:05.950
Are there kits they
can buy or things?

00:09:05.950 --> 00:09:05.996
PROF.

00:09:05.996 --> 00:09:06.650
RAFFAELLO D'ANDREA:
Yeah, there are.

00:09:06.650 --> 00:09:11.080
So, I mean, to do this level
of autonomy is beyond--

00:09:11.080 --> 00:09:13.150
this is cutting-edge research
that we're doing.

00:09:13.150 --> 00:09:16.060
However, you can buy kits
for flying vehicles.

00:09:16.060 --> 00:09:17.990
They're rather inexpensive
now.

00:09:17.990 --> 00:09:21.260
And if you're willing to do
things with a remote control,

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:24.150
human-piloted, right now it's
very difficult to have fully

00:09:24.150 --> 00:09:27.370
autonomous systems, but give it
another two or three years.

